reviewText: The girls of roller derby are on their way to a match in Portland when the long stretch of road they’re on turns out to be a dead end.  They’ve also picked up Chad (Chad Michael Collins, LAKE PLACID 2) and Allie (Austin Highsmith, GANGSTER SQUAD) who were on their way to a cabin somewhere up north before Chad ran his car into a tree.  But once they reach the end of the road all they find is a fence, surrounding an abandoned mental hospital.The van is running on fumes, says Stewart (Adam Key, STRINGING IN THE STREETS), the driver, and the last town was 80 miles back.  They’ll have to spend the night and get help tomorrow.  So they break into the building where they find another girl, Roxy (Olivia Leigh, “Day Break”), hiding out and seemingly traumatized.  They’re all dead, she says, he killed them.The roller derby crew has no idea what she means, but they decide to search the place while Stewart, who is apparently an electrical whiz, gets the security cameras running again (one of the roller girls had the presence of mind to flip the main breaker switch and lo and behold there’s still power) and camps out in the monitor booth.Then the killings start.  They decide to search the grounds outside and there they find Natasha (Nicole Dionne, “Girls Behaving Badly”), the only roller girl who wanted to stay out and skate when they broke into the place, dead with her eyes gouged out.  There is some panic, and Sarah (Nina Hauser, RENT), the tough roller derby broad who’s always up for a fight, thinks Roxy is responsible.  They decide to try the van, even though it’s low on gas, and just get as far away as they can, but the lights were left on and the battery is dead.  So Barbie (Kim Manning, “Flavor of Love”), the fastest one on the team, and Nelson (Ace Gibson, “Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles”), their coach, decide to skate back to town.  At 15-20 mph, they should get their in about 5 hours.  Piece of cake.  Meanwhile, the rest of the crew, Stewart, Sarah, Chad and Allie, stay behind to keep an eye on Roxy.The bodies keep piling up as Allie digs into the history of the place, specifically Room 33, which Roxy mentioned earlier, and discovers there were some LSD experiments going on in there.  Still with no idea how any of this is connected, the gang just tries to keep calm and survive the night until Nelson and Barbie get back.  Unfortunately, when Barbie does show up again, Sarah accidentally knocks her out cold with a baseball bat then, to cover it up, seduces Chad, then goes on an emotional rampage, skating around the locker room and bashing things with the same bat.  Then, on the monitor, they see a man bring Barbie’s body to the front door and lay her out on the ground before sneaking into the building to search for his missing niece.  What he finds, instead, is the business end of Sarah’s bat, then gets tied up only to later be questioned by Allie whom he tells he’s looking for his niece who recently escaped from a nearby mental hospital--man, how many mental hospitals does this area have???--all leading to the big climax where we learn . . . Actually, I’m not even sure what we learn by the movie’s end.  It certainly didn’t make a lot of sense to me.Something about ghosts and possession and multiple personalities?  I don’t know.  I got the feeling that ending was supposed to be some big shocking reveal, but it never came off that way.  To me, it felt more like a jumbled mess of quick cuts that told absolutely no story and meant nothing in the context of this movie.  It felt like there was a whole backstory section that got left on the editing room floor and could possibly have tied everything together.As it is, I only know what I’ve written here.  If there was some sense to be found, I missed it.Edwin Barbini wrote and directed ROOM 33 (executive producer of “Dirty Job”, “Extreme Loggers” and “The Alaska Experiment”) with some help writing from Donnie Dale, who has no pre- nor post-ROOM 33 credits, and it’s probably just as well.  Since it seems most of Barbini’s work is in the documentary-type television show realm, I will assume ROOM 33 was a passion project for him, that he wanted to move into fiction and had this awesome idea for a possibly haunted mental hospital where there may or may not be a killer on the loose.  I think for someone just getting into this type of filmmaking, a slasher flick seems like a no-brainer.  I mean how hard could it be to intro a bunch of interchangeable characters no one will remember, a mysterious killer who takes them out one by one, then film a climactic chase scene?Can’t be that hard, right?Well, I have a feeling it’s probably harder than it seems, at least if I’m judging by the countless movies I’ve seen in this genre.  In fact, I think maybe I’ve just seen too many of these movies, because the effect they’re having is diminished with every one.  Or maybe the movies are getting worse.  I know this one was a dud, for sure.And I think the failing here all comes down to lack of focus in the story.  Or at least lack of explanation.  I feel Barbini had a clear idea of what was going on here, he just did a terrible job of explaining it.  And don’t even get me started on the editing.  Surprise surprise people, what we see and how we see it are elements just as important to telling a story as anything the characters say.  But this thing felt chopped to bits with no transitions that made a lick of sense and not even an ounce of storytelling ability.But story elements aside, there was absolutely no tension here, no suspense, no sense of rising action leading to a big climax against the big bad wolf.  It just sort of . . . ended.  Weak stuff, man.I’ve seen worse acting in cheaper movies, but the cast here certainly aren’t on the path to Oscar gold, that’s for sure.  Everyone here was given their cliché to play, and they played it to the best of their abilities, I’ll give them that, but no one seemed the least bit interested in giving their character anything extra.  These were strictly black and white performances with no depth or emotional connection to the part or the material.Overall, ROOM 33 sinks like a stone in pretty much all respects.  And that’s putting it nicely, because I WANTED to like this one.  Haunted mental hospital?  Yes, please!  Unfortunately the end result was so badly handled, all I really got out of it was that roller derby girls like to dress in short shorts and sports bras.  Blah.

reviewText: I liked this movie, even though it is chocked full of plot holes. The movie is heavy in creepy paranoia atmosphere, and is successful in that area. But when it comes to story, it falters a little.For example, they are 80 miles away from anything....but later in the movie two characters decide to roller blade back to a town.The van picks up two people who wreck their car and drive for several hours, but later, when the two roller bladers decide to go back to the 80 mile away town, they arrive at the wrecked car in minutes.In a scene close to the beginning, you can see a girl standing in a field watching the group. There is no further explanation. The scene is very creepy, but nothing ever comes of it.
summary: Likeable if you don't look too deep

reviewText: Room 33 (Edward Barbini, 2009)I wanted to like Room 33. I really did. You've got a director from the Dick Wolf stable (Arrest and Trial), some really cute women in roller derby gear, an abandoned asylum, and a supernatural serial killer; what's not to like about this setup? Not a thing, you say, and you're right. But the setup is only part of the story; reveal is the other part, and that's where things start to go wrong.Chad (SyFy Original Movie veteran Chad Michael Collins) and Allie (Exorcism's Nicole Dionne) are driving home from college when their car breaks down in the middle of nowhere. A van finally comes along, and of course it's lost; it contains a roller derby team on their way to a match in Portland. (Nice touch. I think there's actually a town called Portland in every state in the union.) The road ends in a big fence and a "Road Closed" sign, and the van's almost out of gas, so the gang go looking for someone who might be able to provide them with a couple of gallons of go to get them back to the last town (which, we are told a number of times, is about fifty miles away). All they find is a long-abandoned building, which they quickly discover was an asylum. With no gas and no prospects, they decide to hole up there, but things get a little freaky when Allie, while exploring, discovers Roxie (uncredited on IMDB) hiding in what used to be the kitchen. She's babbling, and of little use in figuring out the situation, but Allie, a psychology major, takes Roxie under her wing. But Roxie is not the only one in there with them... or is she?The setup is riddled with cliché (the tech guy is a pervert, there's an inevitable romantic subplot between Chad and one of the rollergirls, the handling of which is painfully inept), but it's got decent bones, and the abandoned asylum, despite being used in so many recent horror flicks, is a good one for lots of shots of people wandering around exploring disused passageways and rooms full of assorted crap. It's not as atmospheric or well-done as something likeSession 9orDeadgirl, but it's miles better than, say,LD 50. So we've got something mediocre but watchable for the first half. Then it all turns to dust. As I've already mentioned, the romantic subplot founders fast; the writers, Barbini and first-time scriptwriter Donnie Dale, were entirely confused first about what to do with Allie, and then about what to do with Chad and Barbie. Then comes a jumbled explanation about who the killer actually is (it does eventually make sense, but given that, why not just drop the expository prose altogether?), and all the sudden another character shows up. It's an obvious red herring, but the writers put the exclamation point on said red herring without ever actually doing much with him; you get the feeling his whole raison d'etre in the movie is the one scene where he's the red herring, and they had no idea what to do with him after that.Still, for all that, it's decently-paced and halfway watchable, so I can't bring myself to hate it too much. Besides, did I mention the cute rollergirls? **
summary: Roller girls, don't worry, DJ plays the movies all night long...

reviewText: Room 33 is about a troubled young couple and a roller derby team who get stranded in an abandoned mental hospital where a crazy girl is running around and people are turning up dead sans eyeballs. Good luck figuring out much of anything beyond that. I guess the actual killer is supposed to be the crazy chick's dead father who is living on as one of her multiple personalities and was the head doctor at this place. Why is he dead? Got me. Why is he killing people? No idea. Too bad the script is such a mess, because they had the makings of a decent b-horror flick for the first half. The girls were cute and you start to care about some of them. The acting is poor but not offensive, it was filmed pretty well, but the script and plot holes are what really hurt it. Still, for budget horror you could do a whole lot worse (Secrets of the Clown, dear God).

reviewText: The credits roll with an alternative music sound track (REM type music). The movie has that 70's slasher feel to it. A van full of roller derby babes and a few guys are traveling in the Pacific NW when they come across a wreaked car. They pick up the young couple (never old people) and head down the road only to find a gate/fence is crossing the highway. The group jumps the fence only to find the proverbial abandoned mental institution (where bad things used to happen) out in the middle of zero bars on my cell phone country. Sarah "Crash" smashes a window with her aluminum baseball bat because she decides they might as well spend the night there as they can't all sleep in the van which BTW is very low on gas. They quickly discover they are not alone, there is a psycho there named Roxy who tries to kill Crash, then cowers in fright. As the group tries to figure out what is going on, they foolishly separate etc. etc.Some nice legs in shorts roller skate around. Movie drops the f-bomb, has brief simulated oral sex, and no nudity.Not the worse horror movie out there. If you want to do a theme horror movie night of abandoned mental institutions, you might use this one as a warm up.

reviewText: You've seen this story many times, but that doesn't mean you won't enjoy it yet again.A group of young people (including some eye candy) travel in the forest. Their car breaks down. They wander about and find an abandoned ... (in this case, it's an asylum -- but it could as easily have been a house, hospital, prison, high school, military base, etc.). Night falls. A supernatural entity begins killing them, one by one ...The young people in this case are a roller derby team (the eye candy) and their roadies. And a young couple they meet along the way. It's the usual disparate bunch. The tough girl, smart girl, scared girl, horny guy, nice guy, black guy -- yes, "black" is a character trait in low-budget horror films.Along the way, they also meet a crazy girl.This crazy girl knows about the supernatural entity. This entity seems inspired byThe RingandThe Grudge. Initially, we only glimpse it as it rushes the victim, who is suddenly both dead and grotesquely deformed. Not deformed in as original a way as the victims are inThe Ring-- ROOM 33's makeup effects are low-budget. (Later on, we see this creature's M.O. in more detail, so its victims' wounds make more sense.)ROOM 33 is a forgettable film, and not too original. But it's entertaining and enjoyable. Some nicely creepy atmosphere, and professional acting.
